judge_raw:
{
  "is_true_nota": false,
  "rationale": "Ethical and professional standards require disclosure of intraoperative errors to the patient and accurate documentation in the operative report. Option B states this explicitly, so NOTA is not correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "The clinical picture fits cisplatin-induced ototoxicity in urothelial cancer, and cisplatin’s antitumor effect is DNA cross-linking. DNA cross-linking is not among the options, so none of the other answers is correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Two weeks post-catheterization with AKI, eosinophilia, livedo reticularis, and biopsy showing intravascular spindle-shaped vacuoles (cholesterol clefts) indicates cholesterol crystal embolization. This diagnosis is not listed among the options, so none of the other answers is correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Septic shock with DIC following mucopurulent cervicitis/adnexal tenderness and identification of lipid A indicates gram-negative endotoxin, most consistent with Neisseria gonorrhoeae (or similar gram-negative) rather than any listed organism. None of the options describe gram-negative diplococci on appropriate media (e.g., Thayer-Martin); the others are gram-positive or Bordetella-like and do not fit the presentation."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "The presentation is allergic conjunctivitis, for which the most appropriate initial therapy is topical antihistamine/mast-cell stabilizers and cold compresses, none of which are options. Erythromycin, warm compresses, topical corticosteroids (not first-line), and latanoprost are inappropriate."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": false,
  "rationale": "Cocaine-associated chest pain is treated initially with benzodiazepines and nitrates; nitroglycerin is an appropriate first step among the listed options. Beta-blockers (propranolol, labetalol) are avoided, and diltiazem is not first-line. Therefore, at least one option is correct and NOTA is not."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Unilateral dilation of the right ureter and renal pelvis indicates ipsilateral ureteral obstruction (e.g., ureteral stone), which is not among the options. BPH and urethral stricture cause bilateral hydronephrosis due to bladder outlet obstruction, and renal artery stenosis/diabetic nephropathy do not cause hydroureteronephrosis."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Post-PCI NSTEMI patients should receive dual antiplatelet therapy with a P2Y12 inhibitor and a cardioselective beta-blocker, neither of which is listed. Nifedipine is not indicated post-MI, enoxaparin is not continued after discharge, spironolactone is not indicated with normal LVEF, and propranolol is contraindicated in asthma."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Copper IUD contraindications include pregnancy, active pelvic infection, unexplained uterine bleeding, uterine/cervical malignancy, uterine cavity distortion, copper allergy/Wilson disease, or pelvic TB. History of stroke/VTE, tobacco use, breast cancer, or liver neoplasm are not contraindications to copper IUD (they primarily affect hormonal contraception). Therefore, none of the listed options is correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": false,
  "rationale": "The nail finding is most consistent with periungual fibromas (Koenen tumors) seen in tuberous sclerosis, which are associated with shagreen patches—flesh-colored papules in the lumbosacral region. Therefore option B is a specific correct answer, so NOTA is not."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Confirmatory testing after a positive rapid HIV screen is a Western blot or HIV-1/2 antibody differentiation assay detecting antibodies to viral proteins, not genotyping, Southwestern blot, or Northern blot. Therefore, none of the provided options correctly describe the confirmatory test."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Findings (splenomegaly, teardrop smear implied, marrow fibrosis, JAK2+) indicate primary myelofibrosis; in a 72-year-old with comorbidities, first-line therapy is a JAK2 inhibitor (eg, ruxolitinib) and supportive care. Cladribine, prednisone, and imatinib are inappropriate, and allogeneic stem cell transplant is generally not the next step in an elderly, comorbid patient."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "A chromosome 22 merlin (NF2) mutation predisposes to bilateral vestibular schwannomas, meningiomas, and ependymomas. None of the listed options (renal cell carcinoma, astrocytoma, vascular malformations, telangiectasias) matches these, so none of the other answers is correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Standing decreases venous return, lowering right atrial pressure, LVEDP, and PCWP, while baroreflex-mediated sympathetic activation increases (not reduces) the SA node phase 4 slope. Since options A–D predict opposite changes, none is correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "The described process is genetic reassortment, which requires a segmented viral genome (e.g., orthomyxoviruses, reoviruses). None of the listed viruses (CMV, EBV, HIV, vaccinia) have segmented genomes, so none can undergo this process."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "A calcified mass near the gallbladder in a patient with chronic cholelithiasis suggests porcelain gallbladder, which carries a high risk of gallbladder carcinoma. The diagnosis to exclude first is gallbladder carcinoma, which is not among the listed options. Therefore, none of the other answers is correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": false,
  "rationale": "In allergic asthma, Th2 cytokines such as IL-13 promote class switching to IgE and drive airway hyperreactivity. Among the listed options, IL-13 fits this role best, whereas IL-5 (IgA/eosinophils), IL-2, and IL-10 do not. Therefore, a substantive correct option exists."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "The investigator matched cases and controls on age, socioeconomic background, and family history, which is matching to control confounding. Matching is not listed among the options, and the described design is not stratified analysis, restriction, blinding, or randomization."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "This is acute pericarditis; optimal first-line therapy is a high-dose NSAID plus colchicine. No option offers NSAID + colchicine (A lacks colchicine, C inappropriately uses steroids, and D/E are not indicated), so none of the other answers is correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Somnolence, slurred speech, ataxia, and diminished reflexes with normal vitals and pupils best fit sedative-hypnotic (eg, benzodiazepine) intoxication, which is not listed. The BAC of 0.04% is low for this degree of impairment, and the other options are not as consistent. Therefore, none of the other answers is correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Travel to Africa is associated with endemic Burkitt lymphoma, axillary involvement is a manifestation rather than a risk factor, and female sex is not a known risk for DLBCL. The relevant risks here are advanced age and prior chemo/radiation (not simply a history of breast cancer), which are not offered, so none of the substantive options is correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": false,
  "rationale": "The findings are most consistent with a ventricular septal defect (high-pitched holosystolic murmur at the lower left sternal border in an acyanotic infant with feeding difficulties), which is classically associated with maternal alcohol use. The other choices point to different defects (chromosome 7 deletion→supravalvular aortic stenosis, lithium→Ebstein anomaly, retinoic acid→conotruncal defects)."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "The presentation (Mississippi exposure), urine polysaccharide antigen, and silver/PAS showing macrophages packed with yeast are classic for Histoplasma capsulatum, which is not listed. The other options are inconsistent with the BAL findings and epidemiology."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": false,
  "rationale": "Pneumonia developing after a week in the hospital is hospital-acquired, commonly caused by gram-negative rods such as Pseudomonas aeruginosa or MRSA. Among the listed options, Pseudomonas aeruginosa is the most likely, so NOTA is not correct."
}

{
  "is_true_nota": true,
  "rationale": "Lethargy with disappearance of wheezing in a severe asthma exacerbation suggests impending respiratory failure (silent chest), requiring immediate endotracheal intubation—an option not listed. Needle thoracostomy, bronchoscopy, heliox, or additional steroids are inappropriate here."
}
